     (there you can download all what you need for Bars&Pipes ...)
@endnode

@node "REQUIREMENTS" "Requirements"
@next "INSTALLATION"
@prev "DISCLAIMER"

 @{b}@{u}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

 First at all you need a installed system of Bars&Pipes2.5.
 If you haven't, download it from the WWW:

 www.id.uq.edu.au/~richard/music/bars-and-pipes/index.html

 This  is  Richard  Hagens  website  in  australia.  That   is   the   best
 Tool-programmer I know for Bars&Pipes. There is also the complete material
 to  download   for   programming   tools   and   much   links   to   other
 Bars&Pipes-websites.

 Second you need a XG-Device.

 For Amiga all extern Devices : MU10, MU80, MU90 ...

                    Soundcard : DB-50XG this is the cheapest
                                (in Germany only 200 DM)

 For the DB-50XG card you must be familiary with  building  electronics.  I
 have developed a MIDI-Interface for my own card. If you need my help, mail
 me:

          alfred.j.faust@gmx.de or also valid: j.k.dax@t-online.de

 But be patience with me, I'm not a electronic-concern ....

 It's  good  to  have  a  MIDI-keybord.  (I   now,   there   is   a   tool:
 sparekeys.ptool,  but  is  not  so  handy  if you are willing to make good
 music.)

 Third:
 My XG-Toolset ...

@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Installation"
@next "XGMAINEDITOR"
@prev "REQUIREMENTS"

 @{b}@{u}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

 Simple   put   all   the   tools   in   your   tools-directory   in    the
 Bars&Pipes-directory.

 If you already have installed a earlyer version of  my  XGToolset,  please
 replace  ALL  Tools,  because  I've  made  alterations  in all tools since
 version 1.7. You can also copy the newer version as:

 XG****1.7.ptool

 into the tools-directory.

 But don't try to  install  (in  the  Toolbox)  a  new  and  older  version
 together.  The tools with the same name have the same intern tool-id. That
 will confuse Bars&Pipes.

 The inovatools1.library copy to the LIBS: directory please.  Don't  forget
 it, the XGMain1.7.ptool need this library. By the other way you will get a
 request, that the inovatools1.library was not found.

 Start Bars&Pipes.

 Open the Toolbox (the Icon with the hammer).

 Choose in the menu of the  Toolbox:  "Remove  Tool  ..."  and  remove  all
 XG-***-Editor Tools.

 After that: "Install Tool ..." and install the tools, you want to use.

 That all for installation.

 When you now will experiment with the tools be shure that you NOT work  on
 your  best  song. I think, with the tools you can't make things wrong. But
 all is possible... .

 If you not understand what the slider labels are means, please have a look
 at the explanation of the tools.

 All actions of the tools will be anwers with a tone you can hear.  So  you
 can  hear  the  alteration  in the moment you leave the sliders or a knob.

@endnode
@node "BEGGARSGUIDE" "Beggars Online XG-Guide"

    @{b}@{u}Beggars Online XG-Guide@{uu}@{ub}

    Here is the internet address for the best XG-Guide in the net.

    There is very, very good explained and documented, was SysEx is and how
    to handle.

            http://huizen.dds.nl/~tmm/beg_toc.htm
                                 (not beg_doc...)

    There I've gotten the most information about the sysex-commands.
@endnode

@node "HOWPROGRAMSYSEX" "How program sysex in Bars&Pipes-Tools"
@prev "Main"

  @{b}@{u}How to programm SYSEX in Bars&Pipes Tools@{uu}@{ub}
  by Alfred Faust j.k.dax@tonline.de


  First: I'm a german man, and I am not so good in the english language

  In the "Rules for Tools" manual I found the sentence:

  (In the capture :"Events, Clips, & Tracks  - Events - 'type'")

  "... Only 'EVENT_VOICE' Events flow through the PipeLine; therefore Tools
  need only concern themselves with this one type. ... "

  That isn't whole right. 'EVENT_SYSX' Events are also  flows  through  the
  Pipeline. I found out how to handle this events, sending directly through
  the PipeLine and writing them in the track.

  Here is the result of my (guess)work.

  First make a string that hold the sysex:

  {
      char *sysex;
      ...

      sysex = "F07E7F0901F7";  //this is the Geral-MIDI Reset

      ...

  }

  or:

  {
      char *sysex;
      storage[16];

      ...

      sprintf(storage, "F07E7F0901F7");
      sysex = storage;

      ...

  }

  ( It is very important that you ALWAYS use STRINGS (char) - not int -  or
  BYTE-values.  You  must  ALWAYS  translate  (int  or  BYTE) - values into
  (char).

  Have a look at the source-codes of my XGTools. There you  can  also  see,
  how to put a prop-gadget-value in the SysExString.

  One possibility:

  {
      char *sysex;
      storage[16];
      int value = 2;
      // this can be the value of a slider

      char hexstr[3][2]={"00","01","02"};
      //that are hexvalues as strings!!!

      ...

      sprintf(storage, "F043104C020102%.2sF7", hexstr[value] );


   /*
      this is the sysex for REVERB-time in XG-Devices
      The "%.2" will be replaced by "02" from hexstr-array,
      and then written into storage.

      You can also write:

      sprintf(storage, "F043104C020102%02lxF7", value)

      in this case you don't need the "hexstr"

      The "%02lx" will replaced by the value. Always  a  2  nibble  hexbyte
      will be written on the place, where the %02lx is.

      Example:

      A value of a slider(Prop-Gadget) is given as decimal "20".
      %02lx will be replaced by "14" as hexbyte.
   */

      sysex = storage;

      ... )

  For my routines it MUST be a string. Then put it on the way. 

  These are all functions you need:

  //the clip-routines for writing in the track

  static BOOL lock_clip(struct Clip *clip) {
    Forbid();
    if (clip->locked == 0)
      {
        clip->locked = 1;
        Permit();
        return TRUE;
      }
    else
      {
        Permit();
        return FALSE;
      } }

  static void unlock_clip(struct Clip *clip) {
    clip->locked = 0; }

  //writes sysex into track

  static void insertsysex(char *buff, short size,
                          struct MNXGTool *tool,const LONG time)
  {
   struct StringEvent *event;
   struct String *string;

   event = (struct StringEvent *) (*functions->allocevent)();
   if (event)
   {
    string = (struct String *) (*functions->myalloc)(size + 3, MEMF_CLEAR);
    if (string)
    {
     event->next = NULL;
     event->string = string;
     memcpy(string->string,  buff,  size);
     string->length = size + 2;
     event->type = EVENT_SYSX;
     event->status = MIDI_SYSX;
     event->time = time;
     event->tool = tool->tool.next;
     if (lock_clip(&(tool->tool.track->clip)))
     {
      event->next =
      (struct StringEvent *)tool->tool.track->clip.events.first;

      tool->tool.track->clip.events.first =
      (struct Event *)(*functions->sorteventlist)(event);

      unlock_clip(&(tool->tool.track->clip));
     }
     else
     {
      (*functions->freelist)(event);
     }
    }
   } }

  // the routine for sending SysEx-data thru the pipeline

  static void sendsysex(char *buff, short size,
              struct MNXGTool *tool, const LONG time) {
   struct StringEvent *event;
   struct String *string;

   event = (struct StringEvent *) (*functions->allocevent)();
    if (event)
    {
     string = (struct String *) (*functions->myalloc)(size + 3, MEMF_CLEAR);
     if (string)
     {
      event->string = string;
      memcpy(string->string,  buff,  size);
      string->length = size + 2;
      event->type = EVENT_SYSX;
      event->status = MIDI_SYSX;
      event->time = time;
      event->tool = tool->tool.next;
      WaitTOF();
      (*functions->qevent)(event);
      (*functions->myfree)(string);
     }
    } }

  // THE MOST IMPORTANT TRANSLATION-ROUTINE

  static void  trans_hx(struct MNXGTool *tool,
                        const LONG time, char *sysx, int sw)
  {
    LONG size;
    int a,  b,  x,  y ;
    UBYTE abuf[32];
    char chr[4];
    char *zbuf = NULL;
    struct Event *sysx_event;

  /*
     translate sysexbuffer (there are single chars, with his own hexvalue)
     into hex (always two chars to one hexvalue)

     example: "F0"
     In the string there are two hexvalues :
     0x46 for "F" in the ASCII-table
     0x30 for "0" in the ASCII-table
     But we will send the hex-value "0xF0" AND NOT "0x46 0x30"
     so we must translate ... */


  size = strlen(sysx); zbuf = (char *)AllocVec(size+2,  MEMF_ANY|MEMF_CLEAR);
  if(zbuf)
   {
    CopyMem(sysx,  zbuf,  size);
    b=0;
    for(a=0;a < size;a=a+2)
    {
     chr[0] = zbuf[a];
     chr[1] = zbuf[a+1];

     x=(isdigit((int)chr[0]))? (chr[0]&0xF) : ((chr[0]&0xDF)-55);
     y=(isdigit((int)chr[1]))? (chr[1]&0xF) : ((chr[1]&0xDF)-55);
     //this is the translationscore - don't touch !!!

     abuf[b++] = ((x<<4)|y);
     //writing with bitmanipulation

     }

    FreeVec(zbuf);

    if (sw == 0) sendsysex(abuf,  b,  tool,  time);
    if (sw == 1) insertsysex(abuf,  b,  tool,  time);
    //put hexdata away

   } }


  There are now to possibilities.

  1. Sending through the PipeLine:


  {
      struct my_Tool *tool;
      // a pointer to your Tool-structure

      char *sysex;
      ...

      sysex = "F07E7F0901F7";
      //this is the Geral-MIDI Reset


      trans_hx(tool, functions->timenow, sysex, 0)
      // "0" =  switch for sending
      ...

  }

  If you only need the sendsysex-routine the  clip-routines  are  here  not
  necessary.


  2. Writing in the Track:

  {
    struct my_Tool *tool;
    // a pointer to your Tool-structure

    char *sysex;

    ...

    sysex = "F07E7F0901F7";  //this is the Geral-MIDI Reset

  if ((*functions->areyousure)("write to track ?
                                Play-pointer on right place?"))
        //this is a nice question ...

     {
     if (!functions->running)
         // You CAN'T write into track, if the sequencer is running !!!

       {
     trans_hx(tool, functions->starttime, sysex, 1)
     // "1" = switch for writing

       }
     }

    ...

  }

  If you don't need my comments - kill them ...

  I hope my pain, sweat and many sleepless nights are not only  useful  for
  my own.

@endnode

@node "XGMAINEDITOR" "XG-Main-Editor"
@prev "INSTALLATION"

  @{b}@{u}XG-Main-Editor@{uu}@{ub}                  @{"(picture)" system "SYS:Utilities/Multiview pics/Main.iff"}

  This is the main  tool  of  the  set.  It  is  also  useable  for  normal
  GM-Devices.  (The  difference  to  the  other tools in this toolset: this
  editor works on Controllers and not on  SysEx  -  System  Exclusive  Data
  commands.)

  If you will use this Tool on a General-MIDI device please don't touch the
  "bank"-slider. Also the VarFX has no effect.

  If you are using a early version of my XGToolset, you will find here  the
  most difference.

  First, I was experimenting with the "Inovatools1"  from  Todor  Fay,  the
  main  programmer  of  Bars&Pipes.  I've made available this functions for
  OS3.1. They are near all implemented in Bars&Pipes, only  the  knobs  are
  not  implemented.  Because  these knobs are very easy to handle, I made a
  try in this tool. These knobs are  "screenmode  sensitive".  That  means,
  they are adapting semself to all possible screenmodes. So they are always
  round circles. Isn't it nice ... ?

  To alter the value of a knob, click with the mouse inside  and  move  the
  mouse  around. It is not neccessary to move inside the knob. You can move
  the mouse up to the ends of the screen. So you can made fine alterations.

  I hope you enjoy the knobs, like I do.

  Also a very important alteration is the possibility  to  read  data  from
  track. More a little later.

  Here is the explanation of the knobs and sliders:


  @{"Vol(ume)" link XGMAINVOLUME}    @{"Pan(pot)" link XGMAINPAN}    @{"Rev(erb)" link XGMAINREVERB}    @{"Chor(us)" link XGMAINCHORUS}   @{"Var(iation)FX" link XGMAINVARFX}   @{"Harm(onic)" link XGMAINHARMONIC}


     ( )         ( )          ( )         ( )           ( )            ( )

    @{"value" link XGMAINVALUE}       value        value       value         value          value

  @{"Bri(ghtness)" link XGMAINBRIGHTNESS} @{"Vibr(ato)" link XGMAINVIBRATO} @{"Expr(ession)" link XGMAINEXPRESSION} @{"Att(ac)k" link XGMAINENVELOPE}    @{"Rel(ease)" link XGMAINENVELOPE}    @{"Porta(mento)" link XGMAINPORTAMENTO}


     ( )         ( )          ( )         ( )           ( )            ( )

    value       value        value       value         value          value


                 @{"Name:" link XGMAINNAME}
                 -------------------------------------------------
          @{"Bank" link XGMAINBANK}  |||                                                 value
                 -------------------------------------------------
   ---           -------------------------------------------------
 @{"0" link XGMAIN01}|  |   @{"Prgm#" link XGMAINPROGRAMM}  |||                                                 value
   ---           -------------------------------------------------


      @{"Write to Track" link XGMAINWRITE}            @{"Read" link XGMAINREAD}            @{"Default" link XGMAINDEFAULT}            @{"Test" link XGMAINTEST}


@endnode
@node "XGMAINPORTAMENTO" "Portamento"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Portamento@{uu}@{ub}

    Portamento is a effekt to slide between the tone. This effekt gives for
    example a saxophone more liveliness.

    With the gadget above you switch portamento on or off. If the  text  is
    red portamento is on, and the command "portamento on" is present.

    If it is off the value of the knob have no effect.

    With  the  knob  you  alter  the  slide-time  between  the  two  tones.
    Experiment a little to see (hear), what I mean.

@endnode
@node "XGMAINREAD" "Read from Track"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Read from Track@{uu}@{ub}

    This the most new function I've implemented in the new version.

    Now you can read the data from the track. The tool will only read up to
    the first note in the track. That means it reads all the available data
    before the instrument begin to play.

    That is very useful, if you have a song loaded (normal  B&P-Song  or  a
    MIDI-File - with the help of the Accessory "sMerFF3.1").

    Now put the XGMainEditor in the Pipeline. Open its window and click  on
    "Read".  The  tool  reads  out the data, and you will see (if there are
    data) immediately all knobs and/or sliders  are  jumpes  to  the  right
    position, and the values will be shown.

    That means also:

    - it ist not neccessary, like in the earlier versions, to let the  tool
      stay in the pipeline (and save the song  with  the  tool  -  and  its
      values).

    - you can use this tool also with songs, you have made with the earlier
      version of the XGMainEditor.

    If want (I think so) to write your alterations back to the track, after
    you have worked on the instrument, you have to kill the old data in the
    track before manually.

    (Mark in the Track-Editor - double click in the track, or ENTER if  the
    track  ist highlighted to open the Track-Editor - with the Edit-Markers
    the range, where the instrument-datas are, and Erase - Menu Edit -  the
    range.
    The other way is to use the rubber ... ;-)  )

    Also important: The sequencer stops if you click on Read while  playing
                    a song. Because it is not possible to  read  while  the
                    sequencer is running.

@endnode
@node "XGMAINCHORUS" "Chorus"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Chorus@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the chorus that added to  the  instrument  you  had
    chosen.  The  effect  is, that the instrument will sounds like a choir.
    The sound will be bigger and fater.

    The default value is 0.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINHARMONIC" "Harmonic"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Harmonic@{uu}@{ub}

    Here  you  can  adjust  the  harmonic  uppertones  that  added  to  the
    instrument you had choosen.

    The effect is, how good the self-assertion of  the  instrument  in  the
    song is.

    The default value is 40.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINPAN" "Pan"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Panorama@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the instrument you had choosen  between  right  and
    left.

    The default value is 64. That is the middle.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINREVERB" "Reverb"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the reverb that added to  the  instrument  you  had
    choosen.

    The effect is, how deep in the room the instrument will stay.

    The default value is 40.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINVALUE" "value"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Value@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can see what the current value of the slider or knob is.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINVARFX" "Variantion Effect"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Variation Effect@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the variable effect that added  to  the  instrument
    you had choosen.

    The button must be selected - the text is then red. Otherwise you can't
    hear  anywhat.  Also  you  must  switch  on the System Exclusive in the
    MIDI-Out-Tool, because the command for VarFX on/off is a SysEx-command.

    The default of the slider is 0.

    The default effect ist "Delay LCR". The explanation of all the  effects
    of the XG-Device you will find in the @{"XG-Variation-FX-Editor" link XGVARFXEDITOR} section of
    this guide.

    There you can choose the third effect, that you will use at this time.

    CAUTION !

    When you use the @{"Reverb-" link "XGREVERBEDITOR" 0}, @{"Chorus-" link "XGCHORUSEDITOR" 0} or @{"VarFX-Editor" link "XGVARFXEDITOR" 0}, the effect you  choose
    is for the whole device.

    That means: ALL reverb-, chorus-, or varfx-sliders in other  tools  use the
    effect you had choosen in the Reverb-, Chorus- or VarFX-Editor.

    You can only use one reverbeffect and only one  choruseffect  and  only one
    variationeffect at the same time.

    Because there are "only" 3 effect-processors on the board.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINVOLUME" "Volume"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Instrument Volume@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the instrument volume you had choosen.

    The default value is 100.

    You can try it over 100 but be careful. Some sound are not  good,  when
    the  volume  is  higher then 100. But it is possible that this is, what
    you want.


@endnode

@node "XGMAINBRIGHTNESS" "Brightness"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Brightness@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the brightness of the instrument you had choosen.

    The effect is, how light or dark the instrument sounds.

    The default value is 40.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINVIBRATO" "Vibrato"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Vibrato@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you  can  adjust  the  density  of  vibrato,  that  added  to  the
    instrument you had choosen.

    The default value is 0.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINEXPRESSION" "Expression"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Expression@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can  adjust  the  density  of  expression  you  have  for  the
    instrument you had choosen.

    In the expressionvalue you affect first the maximalvolume but also  the
    timbre  of  the  instrument. Some instruments reacts more other less if
    you work on this slider. Try it out ...

    The default value is 127.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINENVELOPE" "Envelope"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"


    @{b}@{u}Attack or Release or Decay@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can alter the values of the envelope generator.

    A primitive graphic says more:

                    +
                  +   +
                +       +
              +           +
            +               + + + +
          +         |<     >|       + + + + + +
        +            Decay 1                     +
      +                                              +
    +                       |<     Decay2    >|          +

   |<    Attack    >|                         |< Release >|



   The Decay - values you can alter in the @{"Multipart-Editor" link "XGMULTIPARTEDITOR" 0}
   or in the @{"Drum-Editor." link "XGDRUMEDITOR" 0}


   The default value is for Attack and Release 64.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINNAME" "Name"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

   @{b}@{u}Instrument Name@{uu}@{ub}

   It is not very handy to get always the soundtable and find out the  bank
   and the programnumber, and then try if it is the right sound I want.

   At this reason I have insert in the tool all names of all instruments.

   In this field you can see the name of the current choosen Instrument.


@endnode

@node "XGMAINBANK" "Bank"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Bank Number@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can choose the sound bank of the instrument.

    XG-devices have 101 soundbanks. Not all places in the banks have a own
    sound. If there is no sound you will hear the sound of the bank 0. That
    is the GM-soundbank.

    In the case that there is no sound you will see @{b}«empty»@{ub} in the Name-
    field.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINPROGRAMM" "Program"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Program Number@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can choose the programnumber of the instrument you will hear.

    Then you can hear the sound thru your audio-output.

    With the bank-slider you can choose a variation of your sound if  there
    is one. Have a look at your XG-voice-list in the owners manual.

    You have no voice list ???  :(

    It doesn't matter !!! :) I've insert all sound names of the XG-sounds.

    If you see a @{b}«empty»@{ub} in the Name-field then is there no sound, and  the
    XG-Device  use  the  GM-sound  of  bank  0. This name you see, when the
    bankslider is left (=0).

    I think for work with the tools, this is easier  then  hold  the  voice
    list in the hand, to choose the sound.

@endnode
@node "XGMAINVARFXON" "Variationseffect on/off"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Variations effect on/off@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can switch on or off the variations effect.

    If the text is red the Variations effect is on.

    Attention !

    You MUST switch the System Exclusive on in the  MIDI-Out-Tool.  By  the
    other way you will not hear anywhat.

    This switch is the only function in the XGMainEditor  that  works  with
    SysEx-Data.

    The default is  off (text is blue).
@endnode

@node "XGMAIN01" "0/1-button"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Programmnumberstart at 0 or 1@{uu}@{ub}

    At the beginning of  my  work  with  the  MIDI-equipment  I  often  was
    confused by the use of the programnumbers.

    In the track I had to put the numers from 0 - 127, but in  the  manuals
    always the programnumbers are from 1 - 128.

    So I insert this little knob. You can switch between 0 or 1.

    If you switch to 1 the programmnumber (you see in the right) will range
    from 1 to 128 (like in the most soundtables).


    The tool intern always works with the numbers from 0.

    You can use what you want ...

    Default is 0.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINWRITE" "Write to Track"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Write data to track@{uu}@{ub}

    THAT IS THE MOST IMPORTANT KNOB - I think.

    You can write all what you have done to the track.

    Later you  can  alter  all  (controller)data  -  if  you  want  -  with
    Bars&Pipes track-editor or you @{"read them back" link XGMAINREAD} to the tool and work with
    it.

    Before writing you will be ask : Are you shure to write ... ?
@endnode

@node "XGMAINDEFAULT" "Default"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Default@{uu}@{ub}

    I have altered so much, but - panic - what was the values at the beginning
    of my work ???

    Be quiet - press the Default-knob !!

    All sliders jumps to the default-position and the tool sends the default
    to the XG-Device.
@endnode

@node "XGMAINTEST" "Test"
@prev "XGMAINEDITOR"

    @{b}@{u}Test@{uu}@{ub}

    By pressing this knob you will hear some tones.

    I think this knob is not necessary, but at the beginning of my programming
    of this tool, I was like a baby. I used Richard Hages pc3-Tool as model.

    Because I had learned so much by using and studing his toolsourcecode, I
    leave the knob as it is. That is my thanksgiving to Richard Hagen.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBEDITOR" "Reverb-Editor"

    @{b}@{u}The XG-Reverb-Editor@{uu}@{ub}            @{"picture" system "SYS:Utilities/Multiview pics/Reverb.iff"}

    Not all labels of the slider are visibile in all  reverb-effects.  Only
    if you see a label you can alter the value, and it have an effect.

    CAUTION !!!

    First of all you have to choose a reverb-typ. Then  alter  the  values,
    you  want.  After  that  write  it to track. The reason: Every time you
    alter the reverb-typ all values will be altered to default. That  is  a
    "feature" of the DB-50XG-soundcard, not of the tool.

                             @{"Name" link "XGREVERBNAME" 0}       @{"the reverbeffects" link "XGREVERBEFFECTES" 0}
                 @{"       Typ" link "XGREVERBTYP" 0}
                 @{"      Time" link "XGREVERBTIME" 0}
                 @{" Diffusion" link "XGREVERBDIFFUSION" 0}
                 @{" InitDelay" link "XGREVERBINITDELAY" 0}
                 @{" HpfCutoff" link "XGREVERBHPFLPFCUTOFF" 0}
                 @{" LpfCutoff" link "XGREVERBHPFLPFCUTOFF" 0}
                 @{"     Width" link "XGREVERBWIDTHHEIGHTDEPTH" 0}
                 @{"    Height" link "XGREVERBWIDTHHEIGHTDEPTH" 0}
                 @{"     Depth" link "XGREVERBWIDTHHEIGHTDEPTH" 0}
                 @{"  Wallvary" link "XGREVERBWALLVARY" 0}
                 @{" Dry<->Wet" link "XGREVERBDRYWET" 0}
                 @{"  RvReturn" link "XGREVERBRVRETURN" 0}
                 @{"     RvPan" link "XGREVERBRVPAN" 0}
                 @{"   RvDelay" link "XGREVERBRVDELAY" 0}
                 @{"   Density" link "XGREVERBDENSITY" 0}
                 @{" Er/RevBal" link "XGREVERBERREVBAL" 0}
                 @{"  Feedback" link "XGREVERBFEEDBACK" 0}

             @{"Read" link XGREVERBREAD}                @{" Write" link "XGREVERBWRITE" 0}
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBNAME" "Reverb-Name"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb Name@{uu}@{ub}

    Na what ? Of course: Here you can see the name of the reverb-effect.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBTIME" "Reverb-Time"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb-Time@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can alter the reverb - duration.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBDIFFUSION" "Diffusion"

    @{b}@{u}Diffusion@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can alter the width of the hall room, or with other words: you
    can alter between mono <> stereo-hall.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBINITDELAY" "Initial-Delay"

    @{b}@{u}Initial-Delay@{uu}@{ub}

    InitDelay = Initial Delay of the reverb. Try it ...

@endnode

@node "XGREVERBHPFLPFCUTOFF" "Highpassfrequency&Lowpassfrequency Cutoff"

    @{b}@{u}Highpassfrequency & Lowpassfrequency Cutoff@{uu}@{ub}

    HpfCutoff = High - pass - frequency Cutoff
    LpfCutoff = Low  - pass - frequency Cutoff


    A primitive graphic:

    level

      |
      |
      |
      |   ***********************************
      |   *                                 *
      |   *                                 *
      |   *                                 *
      |****                                 ***************
      |
      +------------------------------------------------------  frequency
          |                                 |
          |                                 |
       lowpass                           highpass

    With this slidser you can cut high or low frequencys. The sound of  the
    hall-effect you want, is your rule.

@endnode

@node "XGREVERBWIDTHHEIGHTDEPTH" "Width - Height - Depth"

    @{b}@{u}Width - Height - Depth@{uu}@{ub}

    Here alter the dimensions of your hall - room.

    Only White Room, Tunnel and Basement

@endnode

@node "XGREVERBWALLVARY" "Wall- variation"

    @{b}@{u}Wall - variation@{uu}@{ub}

    Wallvary have only small effect.

    But for finetuning the reverbsound it is necessary.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBDRYWET" "Dry<->Wet"

    @{b}@{u}Dry < - > Wet@{uu}@{ub}

    This is a slider with no effect :(  here ...

    Sorry, I've insert it because there is a SysEx-command for it.

    If you want use "Dry<>Wet", then work  with  the  @{"Multipart-Editor" link XGMULTIPARTEDITOR}  and
    switch VarFX on.

    Dry<->Wet is the level of the directsignal.

    Try it ... (with the Multipart-Editor)
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBRVRETURN" "Reverb - return"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb - return@{uu}@{ub}
    
    The level of the reverb - effect.
    In my XG-Device that has no effect. I don't now why.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBRVPAN" "Reverb - panorama"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb - panorama@{uu}@{ub}

    In what direction the reverb shall sound ...
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBDENSITY" "Reverb - Density"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb-Density@{uu}@{ub}
    
    That is also a parameter that it is not easy to explain. Hear accurate
    please. Try it ... it's for finetuning the stereo impression ...
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBERREVBAL" "Early Reflection / Reverb - Balance"

    @{b}@{u}Early Reflection / Reverb - Balance@{uu}@{ub}

    The balance between the early reflection and the later reverb.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBFEEDBACK" "Feedback"

    @{b}@{u}Feedback@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can alter very good the sound color of the reverb - effect.
@endnode

@node "XGREVERBTYP" "Reverb-Typ"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb-Typ@{uu}@{ub}

    You can choose between 11 Reverb-Effects:

    Hall  1, 2, 3

    Room  1, 2, 3

    Stage 1, 2

    Plate

    Wh.Room = White Room

    Tunnel

    Basemnt = Basement

    Always you choose a new  typ  of  reverb-effect  the  sliders  jump  to
    default. I've made it because the soundcard make it.

    So  it  is  not  neccesary  to  make  a  "default"-knob  like  in   the
    XG-Main-Editor.

@endnode

@node "XGREVERBRVDELAY" "Reverb-Delay"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb-Delay@{uu}@{ub}

 The time between the begin of the sound and the begin of the  reverb.  try
 it ...   ;-)

@endnode

@node "XGREVERBWRITE" "Write"

    @{b}@{u}Write@{uu}@{ub}

    You can now write your work to track.

    Put the play-pointer to the place, you will write on.

    Befor writing you will ask : "Are you shure ..."

    Then you can work in the event-editor  of  Bars&Pipes.  Switch  in  the
    Prefs of the Event-Editor-Window List-Editing on. So you can see better
    all the SysEx-commands.

@endnode

@node "XGREVERBEFFECTES" "The Reverb effects"

    @{b}@{u}Reverb - Effects@{uu}@{ub}

    Hall        : Reverb simulating the resonance of hall
    Room        : Reverb simulating the resonance of a room
    Stage       : Reverb appropriate for a solo instrument
    Plate       : Reverb simulating a metal plate reverb unit
    White Room  : A unique short reverb with a bit of initial delay
    Tunnel      : Simulation of a tunnel space expanding to left and right
    Basement    : A bit of initial delay followed by reverb with a unique
                  resonance
@endnode

@node "XGMULTIPARTEDITOR" "Multi-Part-Editor"

    @{b}@{u}Multipart-Editor@{uu}@{ub}

    This is the biggest tool I've written. That was hard work.
    But it was worth the trouble.
    With this editor you can finetune the sound you want.
    You can create big new sounds.
    With this editor you can reach the core of your XG-Device.

    Before:
    If you will use this editor, you MUST switch on the "System  Exclusive"
    in the MIDI-Out-Tool !!! In the other way the MIDI-Out-Tool will filter
    out all what  the  Multipart-Editor  will  send.  It  works  only  with
    System-Exclusive messages.

    Switch off the "Send MIDI  defaults"  in  the  preferences  menu.  This
    means,  that  always if the sequencer is stopped default values will be
    send to MIDI-OUT. Some of the values, you have written, with this tool,
    will be overwritten.

    I had searched for a long time, why the SysEx, I've written  to  track,
    won't  work,  if  I started the sequencer to play this SysEx (these are
    not to hear) and stopped again.

    !!!!!! ATTENTION !!!!!!

    If you use the XG-Multipart-Editor, don't  use  the  XG-Main-Editor  to
    choose  instruments  in  the same pipeline. It will be run afoul of the
    use oft the  MIDI-Channels.  The  part-number  you  have  used  in  the
    Multipart-Editor   you   can't  use  as  MIDI-channel-number  with  the
    Main-Editor.

    Its equal in the other way. If you  have  used  one  channel  with  the
    Main-Editor,  you  can't  use  this  as  part  and  MIDI-channel in the
    Multipart-Editor.

    example:

    You put the XG-Multipart-Editor to first pipeline  and  choose  on  the
    MIDI-Out-side channel 1.

    You create a complex sound with part 1,  2,  3  to  channel  1  in  the
    Multipart-Editor.

    Now you can't use in any other pipeline MIDI-channel 1,2&3.

    The next MIDI-channel you can  use  in  the  next  pipeline  (with  the
    Main-Editor or other tools) is MIDI-channel 4.

    To avoid confusions I'm strongly recommend not to use both  editors  in
    one  song.  If  you want more instruments and not so complex sounds use
    the XG-Main-Editor in the other case the Multipart-Editor.

    Here some other @{"tips and hints" link "XGMPHINTS&TIPS" 0} for use the XGMultipart-Editor.

    I've arranged the sliders at the top in the order you have to use it.

    In this form you see the window @{"(picture)" system "SYS:Utilities/Multiview pics/multipart.iff"}, when it is opened.

    Here I write the full Name, what the shortcut-label means.

    The red numers or words are the variables.
    Some slider are like a switch.
    I have not insert the real values in the most cases, because I mean, that
    is not necessary in use.

    @{" Part " link "XGMPPart" 0}              @{" MIDI-Channel" link "XGMPMIDICHANNEL" 0}         @{"Write" link "XGMPWRITE" 0}     @{"RESET" link "XGMPRESET" 0}
    @{"NormalVoice" link "XGMPNORMALVOICE" 0}         @{"Poly" link "XGMPPOLY" 0}        @{"Multi" link "XGMPMULTI" 0}

       @{" Name                         " link "XGMPNAME" 0}
       @{" Bank                         " link "XGMPBANK" 0}         @{"Attack  " link "XGMPATTACK" 0}.
       @{" Programnumber                " link "XGMPPROGRAMNUMBER" 0}         @{"Decay   " link "XGMPDECAY" 0}.
       @{" Noteshift                    " link "XGMPNOTESHIFT" 0}         @{"Release " link "XGMPRELEASE" 0}.
       @{" Detune rough " link "XGMPDETUNEROUGH" 0}   @{" Detune fine " link "XGMPDETUNEFINE" 0}         @{"PIniLvl " link "XGMPPITCHENVELOPE" 0}.
       @{" Volume                       " link "XGMPVOLUME" 0}         @{"PAttack " link "XGMPPITCHENVELOPE" 0}.
       @{" Velocity sense depth         " link "XGMPVELOCITYSENSEDEPTH" 0}         @{"PRevLvl " link "XGMPPITCHENVELOPE" 0}.
       @{" Velocity sense offset        " link "XGPMVELOCITYSENSEOFFSET" 0}         @{"PRevTime" link "XGMPPITCHENVELOPE" 0}.
       @{" Velocity limit high          " link "XGPMVELOCITYLIMITHIGH" 0}.
       @{" Panpot                       " link "XGMAINPAN" 0}.        @{"Tune C  " link "XGMPTuning" 0}.
       @{" Note limit high              " link "XGPMNOTELIMIT" 0}.        Tune C#
       @{" Note limit low               " link "XGPMNOTELIMIT" 0}         Tune D
       @{" Dry level                    " link "XGMPDRY" 0}         Tune D#
       @{" Chorus                       " link "XGMAINCHORUS" 0}         Tune E
       @{" Reverb                       " link "XGMAINREVERB" 0}         Tune F
   @{" * " link "XGMPVARFXOFF" 0} @{" Variations effect            " link "XGMPVARFX" 0}         Tune F#
       @{" Vibrato rate                 " link "XGMPVIBRATORATE" 0}         Tune G
       @{" Vibrato depth                " link "XGMPVIBRATODEPTH" 0}         Tune G#
       @{" Vibrato delay                " link "XGMPVIBRATODELAY" 0}         Tune A
       @{" Filter cutoff frequency      " link "XGMPFILTERCUTOFFFREQUENCE" 0}         Tune A#
       @{" Filter cutoff resonance      " link "XGPMFILTERCUTOFFRESONANCE" 0}         Tune B


@endnode

@node "XGMPPart" "Part"

    @{b}@{u}Part@{uu}@{ub}

    "Part" is the part of your sound, not the @{"MIDI-Channel" link "XGMPMIDICHANNEL" 0}.
    You have at all 16 parts available. This parts can you connect
    to the 16 MIDI-channels, allone or in groups.

    Part is the first thing you have to choice in this editor.

    A primitive graphic:


    part 1  ---|
    part 2  ---|-------> MIDI-channel 1
    part 3  ---|


    part 4  ---|
    part 5  ---|-------> MIDI-channel 2


    part 6  -----------> MIDI-channel 3


    part 7  ---|
    part 8  ---|
    part 9  ---|-------> MIDI-channel4
    part10  ---|
    part11  ---|


     .                          .
     .                          .
     .                          .

    and so on - just you like ...

    But you  can't  use  a  part  twice  in  the  same  song,  because  the
    DB-50XG-card (or other XG-Devices) connect the part to the MIDI-channel
    with the same number. The result is: this MIDI-Channel is not to use in
    other ways. Think on that, what I've written at the beginning of the
    @{"Multipart-Editor" link "XGMULTIPARTEDITOR" 0}.


@endnode

@node "XGMPMIDICHANNEL" "MIDI-channel"

    @{b}@{u}MIDI-channel@{uu}@{ub}

    MIDI-channel is the second step you have to do at the beginning of your
    work.

    That means you have to connect a @{"part" link "XGMPPart" 0} to a MIDI-channel.

    CAUTION!
    ONLY THEN you can choose a sound for your current part (!).


@endnode

@node "XGMPNAME" "Name"

    @{b}@{u}Name@{uu}@{ub}

    Like in the other Tools of my toolset, you can here see the name
    of the sound you have choosen.


@endnode

@node "XGMPBANK" "Bank"

    @{b}@{u}Bank@{uu}@{ub}

    Choose here the bank-number of the sound, you will use.
    If there is no sound, you will see an «empty» in the @{"Name" link "XGMPNAME" 0}-field.

@endnode

@node "XGMPPROGRAMNUMBER" "Program-number"

    @{b}@{u}Programmnumber@{uu}@{ub}

    Programmnumber: that is the number of your sound. Please have a look at
    your table in the user-manual.

    A little confusing is, that the programnumber  beginn  at  0,  but  the
    soundtable of YAMAHA begin at 1.

    But because I have insert all soundnames of a XG-device, I think it  is
    not a so great problem.

    In the @{"Main-Editor" link XGMAINEDITOR} of my toolset I  had  insert  a  little  knob,  that
    switch  between 0 and 1. In the use of my Main-Editor I found out, that
    it is not necessary, to have that knob ... I have insert all names  ...
    @endnode

@node "XGMPNOTESHIFT" "Noteshift"

    @{b}@{u}Noteshift@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can shift your instrument in halve-tone-steps up or down.

    What is it good for ?

    If you bring the volume down an shift the instrument as a part of  your
    complex sound some halvetones up or down, you will create exotic sound.

    Test it ...


@endnode

@node "XGMPDETUNEROUGH" "Detune rough"

    @{b}@{u}Detune rough@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can tune your whole instrument in bigger steps up or down.


@endnode

@node "XGMPDETUNEFINE" "Detune fine"

    @{b}@{u}Detune fine@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can tune your whole instrument in very fine steps
    if you want ....


@endnode

@node "XGMPVOLUME" "Volume"

    @{b}@{u}Volume@{uu}@{ub}

    If you not now what "volume" is :-)) - look at the explanation of the
    @{"XG-Main-Editor" link "XGMAINVOLUME" 0}.

@endnode

@node "XGMPWRITE" "Write"

    @{b}@{u}Write@{uu}@{ub}

    Writing your datas to track.

    A word to the data of the Multipart-Editor.

    If you (theoretical) altered all slider in all part,  then  the  editor
    have stored 672 sysex-messages and will write them to track.

    If you open the track editor after writing,  you  will  see  much  much
    sysexdata.   Switch   in  the  preferences  of  the  editor-window  the
    Listediting on. So you can see all data and alter  them  (if  you  want
    ....;)  ).  But I think it is easier to erease the track, and work with
    the tool...

    My suggestion for the work with the Multipart-Editor:

    In the first tact put the RESET-data with the RESET-Tool.

    Then put the play-pointer (the litte read triangle - you  now  ...)  to
    "2"  (second  tact). And then beginn your work with the Multipart-Tool.

@endnode

@node "XGMPVELOCITYSENSEDEPTH" "Velocity sense depth"


    @{b}@{u}Velocity sense depth@{uu}@{ub}

    You have made a complex sound, and you want that  the  sound  you  just
    have  choosen  shall  react to the velocity not so strong like an other
    sound    -

    then alter Velocity sense depth.

@endnode

@node "XGPMVELOCITYSENSEOFFSET" "Velocity sense offset"

    @{b}@{u}Velocity sense offset@{uu}@{ub}

    That is the lowest value for the velocity of your choosen sound.

@endnode

@node "XGPMVELOCITYLIMITHIGH" "Velocity limit high"

    @{b}@{u}Velocity limit high@{uu}@{ub}

    That is the highest value for the velocity of your choosen sound.

@endnode

@node "XGMPVARFX" "Variation effect"

    @{b}@{u}Variation effect@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the variable effect that added  to  the  instrument
    you had chosen.

    You have switch VarFX:on before. Otherwise you can't hear anywhat.

    The default of the slider is 0.

    The default effect ist "Delay LCR". The explanation of all the  effects
    of the XG-Device you will find in the XG-Variation-FX-Editor section of
    this guide.

    Here you can chose the third effect, that you will use at this time.

    CAUTION !

    When you use the Reverb-, Chorus- or VarFX-Editor, the effect you chose
    is for the whole device.

    That means: ALL reverb-, chorus-, or varfx-sliders in other  tools  use
    the effect you had chosen in the Reverb-, Chorus- or VarFX-Editor.

    You can ONLY use ONE reverbeffect and ONLY ONE  choruseffect  and  ONLY
    ONE variationeffect at the same time.

@endnode

@node "XGPMNOTELIMIT" "Note limit low and high"

    @{b}@{u}Note limit low and high@{uu}@{ub}

    With this sliders you can set the lowest or highest note  your  choosen
    instrument  will  sound. So you can use an other sound in the bass then
    in the soprano.

@endnode

@node "XGMPVIBRATORATE" "Vibrato rate"

    @{b}@{u}Vibrato rate@{uu}@{ub}

    You can edit how slow or fast vibrato shall swing.

@endnode

@node "XGMPVIBRATODEPTH" "Vibrato Depth"

    @{b}@{u}Vibrato depth@{uu}@{ub}

    Edit the depth of vibrato here ...

@endnode

@node "XGMPVIBRATODELAY" "Vibrato delay"

    @{b}@{u}Vibrato delay@{uu}@{ub}

    For some  instruments  (especially  natural  instruments  like  violin,
    flute, trumpet ...) it is good, the vibrato beginns a little later, the
    beginn of the sound.

    Here you can edit the timepoint.

@endnode

@node "XGMPFILTERCUTOFFFREQUENCE" "Filter cutoff frequency"

    @{b}@{u}Filter cutoff frequency@{uu}@{ub}

    That is like the @{"Brightness" link "XGMAINBRIGHTNESS" 0} in the @{"XG-Main-Editor" link "XGMAINEDITOR" 0}.

