@node "XGVARFXDELAY" "Delay LCR + LR, Echo, Cross Delay "

    @{b}@{u}Delay LCR, LR  & Echo  &  Cross Delay@{uu}@{ub}

    Delay      : A program that creates two or three delay sound 
                 (Left, Right, Center)
    Echo       : Two delays(L & R) and independent feedback delays for L & R
    Cross Delay: A program that crosses the feedback of two delays


    Here are some differences between the sliderlabels in the different
    effects. So I will explain in alphabetical order:

    Label           Realname

    @{"CchDelay" link "CchDelay" 0}        Central channel Delay
    @{"CchLevel" link "CchLevel" 0}        Central channel Feedback Level
    @{"Dry<->Wet" link "XGREVERBDRYWET" 0}       Balance between directsignal and effectsignal
    @{"EqHigFreq" link "EqHigFreq" 0}       Equalizer high frequency
    @{"EqHigGain" link "EqHigGain" 0}       Equalizer high gain
    @{"EqLowFreq" link "EqLowFreq" 0}       Equalizer low frequency
    @{"EqLowGain" link "EqLowGain" 0}       Equalizer low gain
    @{"FeedbDly1" link "FeedbackDelay1&2" 0}       Feedback Delay 1
    @{"FeedbDly2" link "FeedbackDelay1&2" 0}       Feedback Delay 2
    @{"FeedbLvl" link "CchLevel" 0}        Feedback Level
    @{"HighDamp" link "HighDamp" 0}        High Damp
    @{"Input:L,R,LR" link "Input" 0}    Input: Left, Right, Left&Right
    @{"L->RDelay" link "L>R R>LDelay" 0}       Left to Right Delay
    @{"LchDelay" link "CchDelay" 0}        Left channel Delay
    @{"LchDelay1" link "FeedbackDelay1&2" 0}       Left channel Delay 1
    @{"LchDelay2" link "FeedbackDelay1&2" 0}       Left channel Delay 2
    @{"LchFdbLvl" link "CchLevel" 0}       Left channel Feedback Level
    @{"R->LDelay" link "L>R R>LDelay" 0}       Right to Left Delay
    @{"RchDelay" link "CchDelay" 0}        Right channel Delay
    @{"RchDelay1" link "FeedbackDelay1&2" 0}       Right channel Delay 1
    @{"RchDelay2" link "FeedbackDelay1&2" 0}       Right channel Delay 2
    @{"RchFdbLvl" link "CchLevel" 0}       Right channel Feedback Level
    @{"SndVxtoCh" link "SENDFXTOCHORUS" 0}       Send Variationseffect to Chorus
    @{"SndVxtoRv" link "SENDFXTOREVERB" 0}       Send Variationseffect to Reverb
    @{"VarPan" link "VarPan" 0}          Variationseffect Panorama
    @{"VarReturn" link "VarReturn" 0}       Variationseffect Return
@endnode

@node "CchDelay" "channel delay"

    @{b}@{u}Channel Delay@{uu}@{ub}

    The time between original signal and beginn of the "delayed"
    signal in this channel.
@endnode

@node "CchLevel" "Central channel Level"

    @{b}@{u}Central Channel Delay@{uu}@{ub}

    Here alter the level of the "delayed" signal. This have also an effect
    how often you will the "Delay" hear.

    You can real alter between -64 <-> +64
    That means in this case: the 64 value is the middle.
@endnode

@node "VarPan" "Variations effect panorama"

    @{b}@{u}Variations effect panorama@{uu}@{ub}

    You can influence the main direction of the current choosen effect.
@endnode

@node "VarReturn" "Variations effect Return "

    @{b}@{u}Variations effect return@{uu}@{ub}

    Sorry, ... on my DB-50XG has this no effect. Means the global level
    of the effect signal.
@endnode

@node "FeedbackDelay1&2" "Feedback Delay 1 & 2"

    @{b}@{u}Feedback Delay 1, 2 @{uu}@{ub}

    Feedback Delay 1 & 2 works together. There are two swinging
    and overlapping "Delays".


    A primitive graphic:

    the * are the "Delays"


    LEVEL
     |
     |
     |  *
     |  |  *
     |  |     *
     |  |                 *
     |  |                 |  *
     |  |                 |     *
     |  |                 |
     |  |<---Delay 1----->|               *
     |                                    |   *
     |                                    |   |   *
     |                         Delay 2--->|---|<--
     |
     |
     ----------------------------------------------------------TIME
@endnode

@node "HighDamp" "High frequencys damp"

    @{b}@{u}High frequencys damp@{uu}@{ub}

    SORRY, that has no effect on my DB-50XG ... means the damp of
    the high frequencys.
@endnode

@node "EqLowFreq" "Equalizer low frequency"

    @{b}@{u}Equalizer low frequency@{uu}@{ub}

    You can choose the low frequency, the gain slider shall effect to.
    So you not only can adjust the level of the low frequencys. You
    can also the frequency range adjust, like a parametric equalizer.

    That all effects to the effectsignal, not to the original signal.
@endnode

@node "EqHigFreq" "Equalizer high frequency"

    @{b}@{u}Equalizer high frequency@{uu}@{ub}

    You can choose the high frequency, the gain slider shall effect to.
    So you not only can adjust the level of the high frequencys. You
    can also the frequency range adjust, like a parametric equalizer.

    That all effects to the effectsignal, not to the original signal.
@endnode

@node "EqHigGain" "Equalizer High Gain"

    @{b}@{u}Equalizer High Gain@{uu}@{ub}

    This is just like a volume slider, but it works on the high 
    frequencys you had adjusted with the @{"EqHigFreq-slider" link "EqHigFreq" 0}.
@endnode

@node "EqLowGain" "Equalizer low gain"

    @{b}@{u}Equalizer low gain@{uu}@{ub}

    This works like a volume controller, but it has an effect to the
    low frequencys you have adjusted with the @{"EqLowGain-slider" link "EqLowGain" 0}.

    It effects to the effect-signal not to the original signal. Hear
    on the "Delays".
@endnode

@node "Input" "Input"

    @{b}@{u}Input@{uu}@{ub}

    The red label shows the direction, from where the first "Delay"
    comes.

    L  from left
    R  from right
    LR means from Left and Right at the same time.
@endnode

@node "L>R R>LDelay" "Left to Right and Right to Left Delay"

    @{b}@{u}Left to Right and Right to Left Delay@{uu}@{ub}

    Must I explain it ?   ;-)

    The time between the delays.

    L->R  from left to right
    R->L  from right to left

    so you can make a asymetrical swinging of the delays.
@endnode

@node "XGVARFXREFLECTION" "Early Reflection 1 & 2"

    @{b}@{u}Early Reflection 1 & 2@{uu}@{ub}

    An effect that only produces only the early reflection of reverb

    Labelname       Realname

    @{"ERTyp:   " link "ERTyp" 0}       Early Reflection Typ
    @{"RoomSize " link "Roomsize" 0}       Room Size
    @{"InitDelay" link "InitDelay" 0}       Initial Delay
    @{"Diffusion" link "XGREVERBDIFFUSION" 0}       Diffusion
    @{"FeedbLevl" link "FeedbLevl" 0}       Feedback level
    @{"HpfCutoff" link "XGREVERBHPFLPFCUTOFF" 0}       High pass frequency cutoff
    @{"LpfCutoff" link "XGREVERBHPFLPFCUTOFF" 0}       Low pass frequency cutoff
    @{"Dry<->Wet" link "XGREVERBDRYWET" 0}       Dry Wet Balance
    @{"VarReturn" link "VarReturn" 0}       Variations effect return
    @{"VarPan   " link "VarPan" 0}       Variations effect panorama
    @{"SndVxtoRv" link "SENDFXTOREVERB" 0}       Send variationseffect to Reverb
    @{"SndVxtoCh" link "SENDFXTOCHORUS" 0}       Send variationseffect to Chorus
    @{"Liveness " link "Liveness" 0}       Liveness
    @{"Density  " link "XGREVERBDENSITY" 0}       Density
    @{"HighDamp " link "HighDamp" 0}       High Damp
@endnode

@node "ERTyp" "Early reflections typ"

    @{b}@{u}Early reflections typ@{uu}@{ub}

    There are 6 red labeled Early Reflections types:

    Label   Real name
    --------------------------------------------------------------------

    S-H     Short Hall: the time of the early reflection is "short"

    L-H     Large Hall: the time of the early reflection is "large"

    Rdm     Random    : here you will hear a random early reflection
                        You can't say before what you will hear in the
                        next time.

    Rvs     Reverse   : the early reflection sounds like when the
                        taperecorder plays it reverse.

    Plt     Plate     : it is like a hall the generated with the
                        hall-plate, a early method to generate a hall-
                        effect, before there where good computers.

    Spr     Spread    : the early reflection will be "spreaded"


    Like on other places I will say:

    Your rule is the sound you want to generate....  :-)
@endnode

@node "Roomsize" "Roomsize"

    @{b}@{u}Roomsize@{uu}@{ub}

    Na, what ?

    Right, here you can alter the roomsize.  ;-)
@endnode

@node "InitDelay" "Initial Delay"

    @{b}@{u}Init Delay@{uu}@{ub}

    The time between the original and the beginning of the effect.
@endnode

@node "FeedbLevl" "Feedback Level"

    @{b}@{u}Feedback Level@{uu}@{ub}

    The Feedback to the effect-processor. 
    
    In first you can alter the sound color of  the  effect,  in  second  is
    there  a possibility to generate many early reflection up to a standing
    no ending repetition.

@endnode

@node "Liveness" "Liveness"

    @{b}@{u}Liveness@{uu}@{ub}

    It is just a parameter that is not so easy to explain. You  should  try
    it.

    My meainig is it affects to the impression of the effect. Liveness ...

@endnode

