    @{"SndCh>Rev" link "SndCh>Rev" 0}   Send Chorus to Reverb
    @{"    Input" link "ChorInput" 0}   Input
    @{"LFOPhDiff" link "FlangerLFOPhDiff" 0}   Low Frequency Oscillator Phase Difference


    @{"Read" link XGCHORUSREAD}    @{"Write" link XGCHORUSWRITE}
@endnode
@node XGCHORUSREAD "Read"

    @{b}@{u}Read@{uu}@{ub}

    Like in the other tools - this is the new function in the version 1.7.

    Now you can read XGChorus-data from track if there are any. The tool is
    able  to  read  data,  which are not from "itself". Because all XG-data
    must have the same SysEx-structure this is possible.

@endnode
@node XGCHORUSWRITE "Write"

    @{b}@{u}Write@{uu}@{ub}

    After you have done all your choose for the effect, you  can  write  it
    down in the track.

    Before move the playpointer at the right  place.  This  is  the  moving
    triangle while playing the sound.

@endnode

@node "ChorRetur" "Chorus Return"

    @{b}@{u}Chorus Return@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can alter the global level of the choosen effect.
@endnode

@node "SndCh>Rev" "Send Chorus to Reverb"

    @{b}@{u}Send Chorus to Reverb@{uu}@{ub}

    You can send the signal to the reverb effectprocessor. So you can use, if
    you want, the reverbeffect you have choosen in the XG-Reverb-Editor twice.
@endnode

@node "ChorusEffects" "The Chorus effects"

    @{b}@{u}The Chorus effects@{uu}@{ub}

    Chorus  : Conventional chorus program that adds natural spaciousness
    Celeste : A 3-phase LFO adds modulation and spaciousness to the sound
    Flanger : adds a jet-airplaine effect to the sound
@endnode

@node "XGDRUMEDITOR" "Xg-Drum-Editor"

    @{b}@{u}The XG-Drum-Editor@{uu}@{ub}           @{"picture" system "SYS:Utilities/Multiview pics/Drum.iff"}

    This is the editor for the drummers or drumfreaks.
    Here you can choose the DrumKit you will work with.
    Here you can work on every sound of every drumvoice that is
    stored in the ROM of the YAMAHA-soundcard DB-50XG.

    !!!!! First off all !!!!!
    The Homeplace of this tool is track 10 - the drumtrack.
    In a other track that tool will not work !!!

    CAUTION !!!
    This tool works, like other tools (except the XG-Main-Editor),
    with SysEx-commands. All action you  do results a SysEx-command,
    that will be written in the track (if you write to track).
    That means there will be very much SysEx-commands written to
    track(theoretical more then 2600 different).

    You MUST at first choose the instrument !!

    The order you work away is free. But in the beginning the tool MUST now
    on wich Instrument on wich Kit you will work.
    My suggestion is as third to choose if you want use the Variationseffect
    and switch @{"VarFX on or off" link "DrumVFXon" 0}. By default the effect is switched on.

    The sliders:
    I have written here the realname not the labelname

    (the drumset-gadget I've removed, because there is only one drumset  in
    my DB-50XG)

            @{"Name                      " link "DrumName" 0}.
            @{"Instrument number         " link "DrumInstrument#" 0}.
            @{"(Drum) Kit                " link "DrumKit" 0}.

            @{"Pitch Course" link "XGMPDETUNEROUGH" 0}                    @{"Key On Assign" link "DrumAlternate" 0}
            @{"Pitch Fine" link "XGMPDETUNEFINE" 0}                      @{"Receive Note Off" link "DrumRcvNoteoff" 0}
            @{"Volume" link "XGMPVOLUME" 0}                          @{"Receive Note On" link "DrumRcvNoteon" 0}
            @{"Alternate" link "DrumAlternate" 0}
            @{"Panpot" link "XGMAINPAN" 0}
            @{"Reverb" link "XGMAINREVERB" 0}
            @{"Chorus" link "XGMAINCHORUS" 0}
            @{"Variations effect" link "DrumVarFX" 0}               @{"VFX:" link "DrumVFXon" 0}

            @{"Filter Cutoff" link "XGMAINBRIGHTNESS" 0}                       @{"Default" link "DRUMDEFAULT" 0}
            @{"Filter Resonance" link "XGMAINHARMONIC" 0}                    @{" Write " link "DrumWrite" 0}
            @{"Attack" link "XGMAINENVELOPE" 0}                              @{"  Read " link XGDRUMREAD}
            @{"Decay 1" link "XGMAINENVELOPE" 0}
            @{"Decay 2" link "XGMAINENVELOPE" 0}
@endnode

@node "DrumVarFX" "Variations effect"

    @{b}@{u}Variations effect@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can adjust the variable effect that added to the instrument you
    had choosen.

    The little button left of the slider must be selected. Otherwise  you can't
    hear anywhat.

    The default of the slider is 0.

    The default effect ist "Delay LCR". The explanation of all  the  effects of
    the  XG-Device  you  will find in the @{"XG-Variation-FX-Editor" link "XGVARFXEDITOR" 0} section of
    this guide.

    There you can choose the third effect, that you will use at this time.

    CAUTION !

    When you use the @{"Reverb-" link "XGREVERBEDITOR" 0}, @{"Chorus-" link "XGCHORUSEDITOR" 0} or @{"VarFX-Editor" link "XGVARFXEDITOR" 0}, the effect you  choose
    is for the whole device.

    That means: ALL reverb-, chorus-, or varfx-sliders in other  tools  use the
    effect you had choosen in the Reverb-, Chorus- or VarFX-Editor.

    You can only use one reverbeffect and only one  choruseffect  and  only one
    variationeffect at the same time.
@endnode

@node "DrumAlternate" "Alternate"

    @{b}@{u}Alternate@{uu}@{ub}

    SORRY .... :-(

    This is such a slider that have no effect on my DB-50XG.

    I have insert it, because there is a sysex-command. And it is
    possible that on other devices it will have a effect.
@endnode

@node "DrumRcvNoteoff" "Receive Note off"

    @{b}@{u}Receive Note off@{uu}@{ub}

    In some cases a instrument needs a note off command.
    (Example: Snare Roll)

    The most drum voices are pulse code modulated sounds.
    That means there is a whole sample that will be played, when
    you push a key. You can't stop it, because it is to short.
    Example a Bass Drum Beat.

    But with @{"Attack - Decay 1 & 2" link "XGMAINENVELOPE" 0} you are able to influence the
    length of the sound.
@endnode

@node "DrumRcvNoteon" "Receive Note on"

    @{b}@{u}Receive Note on@{uu}@{ub}

    When do you need "Note on" switched off ??? ...

    I think, only when you will switch off a instrument in the Kit.
@endnode
@node "DrumName" "Name:"

    @{b}@{u}Name:@{uu}@{ub}

    Like in other tools I have insert all Instrument Names.
    Because it will be easier to handle in use.
@endnode

@node "DrumInstrument#" "Instrument number"

    @{b}@{u}Instrument number@{uu}@{ub}

    The red label on right is the key, on that you will hear that
    instrument.

    C3 is the middle of the keyboard and in the most cases there is
    a marker.

    C3 is the note in the middle of the notesystem.
    It have one helpline under the violin-system,
    it have one helpline upper the bass-system.
@endnode

@node "DrumKit" "Drum Kit"

    @{b}@{u}Drum Kit@{uu}@{ub}

    There are 9 different Drum Kits available and 2 Soundeffect 
    voice kits

    Standard Kit
    Standard2 Kit
    Room Kit
    Rock Kit
    Electro Kit
    Analog Kit
    Jazz Kit
    Brush Kit
    Classic Kit
    Sound effect voices 1
    Sound effect voices 2

    !!! CAUTION !!!

    IF YOU CHOOSE A KIT THE XG-DEVICE GET THE STORED DEFAULT VALUES.
    ALL WORK YOU HAVE DONE BEFORE WILL BE LOST !!!!
    THAT IS ONE REASON YOU HAVE FIRST TO CHOOSE THE INSTRUMENT AND
    THE KIT.
@endnode

@node "DrumVFXon" "Variationseffect on or off"

    @{b}@{u}Variationseffect on or off@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you have the possibility to switch the Variationseffect on or off.

    !!! CAUTION !!!

    This is the main switch for this effect. That means if you here switch
    the VarFX off it is general off.

    Be warned ..... ;)
@endnode

@node "DRUMDEFAULT" "Default"

    @{b}@{u}Default@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can switch to the default values of the current choosen 
    instrument.

    Not like with the @{"Kit-slider" link "DrumKit" 0}. There will be ALL values off ALL instruments
    turned to default.
@endnode
@node XGDRUMREAD "Read"

    @{b}@{u}Read@{uu}@{ub}

    If there any data for this tool in the track, you can  read  them  into
    the tool, to work on them.

    This is the new function in version 1.7

@endnode

@node "DrumWrite" "Write"

    @{b}@{u}Write@{uu}@{ub}

    If you are ready with you work, you can write the values to track.

    Before you will be ask: "Are you shure ...".

    I had say it before: There is the possibility, that there will be
    written very much data to the track.
@endnode

@node "Suggestions" "Suggestions for use"

    @{b}@{u}Suggestions for use@{uu}@{ub}

    The soundcard need a little time to react to all the messages.

    So I suggest:

    If you are beginning your work, put first the Reset-Tool to track 1
    (to this track I write all sysexcommands except the Drum-Tool-sysex).
    Put the Play-pointer to the beginning (bar 1).
    Write the Reset-sysex to bar 1. In the other way you must always
    first reset the card manually.

    Put the play-pointer one bar after the last sysexcommand you have
    written to the track (open the track-editor - doubleklick on track;
    switch on "System Exclusive" in the "show"-menu, and now yo can see
    where is the end of the sysex), than work away in the same way.

    It is possible, if you are using all editors, you have at least up to
    4 or 5 bars with sysex-commands.
    Begin the song after all sysex. In the other way you can hear some
    noises you don't want to hear.

    You can also make a separate sysex-file for your song, that played before
    you will play your song.

    That have the advantage that you can store for example a effectset and/or
    drumset for many songs you will write. (The disadvantage is you have always
    2 files to load.)
@endnode

@node "Load&Save" "Load and Save Datas of the tools"

    @{b}@{u}Load and Save Datas of the tools@{uu}@{ub}

    I've no made the possibility to save the datas of the tools in separate
    files.

    But that doesn't mean, that you can't save the datas. In  this  version
    1.3  I've  altered all tools so, that, if you let the tools stay in the
    pipeline:

    - Bars&Pipes stores all slidervalues with the song.
    - Bars&Pipes remember all, what you have done.

    That means, if you want to break your work on a song or sound or effect
    (to  work away later), let all XGTools, you have used, in the pipeline,
    write in all tools the data to track (all sysex to this track  that  is
    connected  to MIDI-channel 1) and save the song. If you in a later time
    will work away, load the song and work away :-)..

    The disadvantage of this method is: the size of the song will  increase
    by each tool, that would be stored with the song.

    The new read-function since version 1.7 makes  your  life  easier.  You
    MUST NOT save the tools with the song. You can read your data back into
    the tool later ...

    If you want to hear your stored sounds, start the sequencer first up to
    this point, all sysex-commands have passed the MIDI-Out.

    Is easy, isn't it.

    So I hadn't to write a save and load routine. That makes my work
    easier.

    The disadvantage of this is, that always some additional data will be
    stored in the song, but I mean it's not so much. If you use ALL tools I
    think it will be not more then 3 Kbyte.

    If you have the absolute last version of your song, you can (if you
    want) remove the tools and save up to 3 Kbyte.

    !!! IMPORTANT !!!

    If you work away with a tool:

    Before you write the new values to track, delete the old in the track,
    because the tools are not overwrite the old values. The new values will
    be added. So it is possible, that the new and the old values will
    confuse the XG-Device and/or the Bars&Pipes.

    For this case it is good to now what wich values are from. I suggest to
    write a little note in the Lyrics-line above the sysex it means
    ("multipart, reverb ...") to find out later, from wich tool the sysex
    in the track is.
@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@prev "Main"

    @{b}@{u}HISTORY@{uu}@{ub}

Some small alterations where made since V.1.1:
    - in XGMain-Editor: removed writing reset values in each track,
                        use for this the XGReset.ptool
    - in the Guidefile: some additions in capture XGMultipart

Since the version 1.2
    - removed some small bugs
    - since this time I (Alfred Faust) write the tools alone, without my son
      Matthias, he is a student of computer sience.

Since the version 1.3
    - all slidervalues of ALL XGTools will be stored with the song.
    - additions made in the guidefile

Since the version 1.4
    - made some alterations in XGChorus, XGReverb & XGVarFX because
      the save and restore won't work proper, the slidervalues where
      stored, but the sysex-commands where not stored;
      now both will be stored, the slidervalues and the SysEx-commands,
      now you can write to track the SysEx-commands proper after reloading
      a saved song and worked away;

Since the version 1.5
    - I've altered the XG-Multipart-Editor
      added the missing 4 sliders of the Pitch Envelope Generator
    - added a new Tool: "XG-Controller-Panel"
      now really ALL functions of the DB-50XG-Board (I hope also of other
      XG-Devices, that base on that board - MU-10, MU-50) are reachable.
      (like in other Tools data can be written to track and save with the
      whole song)

since the version 1.7
    - removed some bugs in all tools
    - in all tools big alterations
    - added into ALL tools the READ-function, to read data back into the tools
      - it doesn't matter, if the data are not from tool written before
      - each tools is able to identify the right data
    - mainly altered the XG-Main-Editor to use knobs instead of sliders.
      These Knobs are part of the Inovatools1 and are not included in the
      Rules for Tools (blueribbon.library).
      If you are interested in this routines please mail @{"me" link WHOIAM 0}.

@endnode
@node "XGCONTROLLERPANEL" "XG-Controller-Panel"
@prev "Main"

    @{b}@{u}XG-Controller-Panel@{uu}@{ub}

    This is now the last tool, I wrote since Version 1.5.

    -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    The data, the tool is working on, are Multipart-data. So  you  can  use
    this  tool  ONLY together with the @{"Multipart-tool" link XGMULTIPARTEDITOR}. The partnumbers, you
    use here, are the same you use in the Multipart-tool.

    At this reason use this tool AFTER you have made  your  work  with  the
    Multipart-tool.

    -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    You can assign with this tool 5 often altered parameters  to  different
    control-datas.  That  is  why SystemExclusive-commands are will disturb
    the datastream flowing throught the pipeline. In the  most  cases,  you
    will hear some uncontrolled noises, when a SysEx-command is transmitted
    during a song.

    The reason is, the length of a SysEx-command is in  the  most  cases  8
    bytes.

    The  length   of   controller-,   modulationswheel-,   aftertouch-   or
    pitchbend-datas  are  only  3  bytes  long,  and they won't disturb the
    datastream.

    So you can assign that:

    Pitch Control,
    Filter (cutoff frequence) control,
    Amplitude (Volume),
    LFO Phase Modulation,
    LFO Frequence Modulation or
    LFO Amplitude Modulation

    are controlled by:

    Pitch Bender,
    Modulations Wheel,
    Poly Aftertouch,
    Channel Aftertouch (Mono Aftertouch),
    Assignable Controller 1 or
    Assignable Controller 2

    In the 2 last cases you can choose also a controller  number,  to  wich
    controller you will assign the parameter.

    Now to the tool itself. If you are familiary with the other  tools,  it
    is not to hard to understand.

    All what you do will be quitted with a control tone, like in the  other
    tools. In the same time the affected SysEx-command will be sended out.

    @{"Picture" system "SYS:Utilities/Multiview pics/panel.iff"}

    The interface with its gadgets:

    @{"part-slider" link "XGCPPart" 0}         Controlled by   Nr.    Range       (Val)

    Pitch-Bend-Contr   |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"     O      " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0} s(emi)t(ones)
    Filter CutoffFrq   |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"     O      " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0} ce(nt)
    Amplitude-Volume   |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"     O      " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0}.
    LFO Phase Modul.   |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"O           " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0}.
    LFO FrequenceMod   |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"O           " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0}.
    LFO AmplitudeMod   |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"O           " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0}.

    -------------------------------------------------------------------
    Connect to Part    |@{"             O" link "XGCPVarFXPart" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPVarfxValue" 0}.

      VarFX Control    |@{"              " link "XGCPContrBy" 0}||@{"   " link "XGCPNr." 0}| |@{"     O      " link "XGCPRange" 0}| @{"   " link "XGCPValue" 0}.

    --------------------------- Receive -------------------------------

    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Program Change       @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Modulation       @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Hold 1
    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Bank Select          @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Portamento       @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Soft Pedal
    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Channel Aftertouch   @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Sostenuto        @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Pitch Bend
    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Poly Aftertouch      @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Control Change
    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Volume               @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Note Message
    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Pan                  @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} RPN                    @{"Read" link XGCTRLREAD}           @{"SysDef." link "XGCPSysDef" 0}
    @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} Expression           @{"*" link "XGCPReceive" 0} NRPN                   @{"Write" link "XGCPWrite" 0}          @{"PartDef" link "XGCPDefault" 0}

@endnode
@node XGCTRLREAD "Read"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Read@{uu}@{ub}

    If there any data for this tool in the track, it will be identyfied and
    stored into to tool.

    The data are Multipart-data.

    The tool only collect data up to the first note.

@endnode
@node "XGCPPart" "Part-Slider"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Part@{uu}@{ub}

    That is the part of your sound, you have choosen in the @{"Multipart-tool" link XGMULTIPARTEDITOR},
    NOT  the  MIDI-Channel.  The assigns of the controllers are possible to
    each of the 16 parts.

    Choose at first the part you will work on.

    You MUST have choosen before with the @{"Multipart-Editor" link "XGMULTIPARTEDITOR" 0} a instrument.
    By the other way you can't hear what you do in this tool.

@endnode

@node "XGCPContrBy" "Controlled by"
@prev "XGCPPart"

    @{b}@{u}Conrolled by@{uu}@{ub}

    If you click in this gadget a menu pops up, and you can choose, by what
    the parameter shall be controlled.

    There in two gadgets default entrys. If you want  use  them,  you  MUST
    chosse them again.

    After that you must choose the control range.

    -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    The tool registers all choose you have made. Later, if you  write  your
    datas  to  track,  the  tool  only writes that datas to track, you have
    touched.

@endnode

@node "XGCPNr." "Assignable Controller number"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Assignable Controller number@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can choose one of the controllers up to number 95.

    You  can  insert  in  the  track-editor  controller-data  (for  example
    controller  45)  (Read  in  your  Bars&Pipes-Manual  please,  how to do
    that.), and assign with the help of this  tool,  that  the  "Assignable
    Controller1" shall affect to "LFO Phase Modulation" by this data.

    Choose:
    -------

                   Controlled by      Nr.

    LFO PhaseMod   Assignable Ctrl1   45

    Easy .... isn't it ?  ;)

    CAUTION !!!

    You  can  assign  to  each  Assignable  controller1  or  2   only   one
    Controller-Nr. in one part !!

    Example:
    --------
    wrong !
    Filter Control Assignable Ctrl1   45
    .      .       .          .       .
    LFO AmplitMod  Assignable Ctrl1   24

    right !
    Filter Control Assignable Ctrl1   45
    .      .       .          .       .
    LFO AmplitMod  Assignable Ctrl1   45

    This is also important for the selection in the "VarFX Control"
    section !!
    But the two different Assignable Controllers can have to different
    numbers, and it is possible to assign them to different parameters.

    @{u}Example:@{uu}

    Pitch-Bend-Control  Assignable Ctrl1  34
    Filter  CutOffFrq   Assignable Ctrl2  36
    Amplitude-Volume    Assignable Ctrl2  36

    .                   .          .      .

    LFO AmplitudeMod    Assignable Ctrl1  34

@endnode

@node "XGCPRange" "Range"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Range@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can choose how much the assigned controller  shall  influence.

    For example:

    Range of Pitch-Control (in semitones - st) 2 (controlled by Modulations
    wheel) means:

    The whole Range of your Modulationswheel on  your  keyboard  alter  the
    pitch of the sound in the range of 2 semitones or one whole tone.

    If you are  not  so  familiary  with  this,  I  strongly  recommend  to
    experiment very much.

    Then you will be enjoyed, what you  all  can  do  with  your  XG-Device
    - Thanks to YAMAHA.

@endnode

@node "XGCPValue" "Value"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Value@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you see the value of your choice of the @{"range" link "XGCPRange" 0}.

    In the first line the value means semitones (st) up or down.

    In the second line the value means cent. Its a big range from -9600  to
    9450 but in steps of 150.

    The other lines shows values from 0 - 127.

@endnode

@node "XGCPReceive" "Receive - control"

    @{b}@{u}Receive - control@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can switch on or off, what data the XG-Device shall recieve in
    the choosen @{"part" link "XGCPPart" 0}.

    If you have made a sound with the @{"Multipart-Editor" link XGMULTIPARTEDITOR}, that have 3  parts,
    so  you  can  here  make,  that for example the data of the "Assignable
    Controller 1" Nr. 45 only affect the  instrument  of  the  third  part.
    Switch off the "Control Change" in part 1 & 2.

@endnode
@node "XGCPWrite" "Write-gadget"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Write@{uu}@{ub}

    Like in the other tools, here you can write all, what you have done  to
    the track, the XG-Controller-Panel is placed.

    Move the song pointer before to that place, you will writing to.

    Then click on the "Write"-gadget. For your security  you  will  be  ask
    "Are you shure ..." before writing.

    Like on other places I recommend to put all SysEx-data to track 1.

    NB: If you have switched off Receive:"Note  Message"  in  a  part,  you
        can't hear the control-tone for this part...

@endnode

@node "XGCPDefault" "Default-gadget"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Part-Default@{uu}@{ub}

    If you will fast put all gadgets and sliders of the current part  (they
    are also gadgets ...;) ) to the default values click on this gadget.

    Default at this place means:
            -all what you see will be sended to the XG-Device.
            -ALL range values are sended to default
            -Assignable Controller 1 & 2 - "Nr." are switched to 0
             (no controller)


@endnode

@node "XGCPSysDef" "System Default gadget"

    @{b}@{u}System Default@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you can put all values of the whole tool to that state, like after
    a Reset. (It affects only the data, that are "owned" by the tool.

    The following data of ALL parts will be set to default:

    - Pitch will be controlled by Pitch-Bender with a range of 2 semitones
    - LFO Phase Modulation will be controlled by the Modulations Wheel with
      a range of 10
    - Assignable Controller 1 - Nr. will be set to Controller 16
    - Assignable Controller 1 - Nr. will be set to Controller 17

    ! IMPORTANT !

    This "reset" will take a while, please be patient ...


@endnode

@node "XGCPVarFXPart" "Connect to Part"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Variations effect connect to part@{uu}@{ub}

    Once again : This works together with the @{"Multipart-Editor" link XGMULTIPARTEDITOR}.

    You can control the variationseffect you have  choosen  for  the  whole
    XG-Device in the part of your choice with :

    - Pitch Bender,
    - ModulationsWheel,
    - Channel Aftertouch or
    - an Assignable Controller (1 & 2)

    If you draw the slider to right end, you will see a "--". That means,
    the connection is off.

    That means also, if the connection is made to a  part  (not  off),  the
    Variationseffect ONLY works in the choosen part, NOT in other.

    In the case of the Assignable Controllers the Controllernumber  of  the
    part will be used, that you have (eventually) choosen in a part before.

    @{u}Example:@{uu}

    Above you have choosen in part 3: the  Pitch  shall  be  controlled  by
                                      Assignable Controller 2, Nr. 25

    If you now choose: VarFx in  part  3  shall  controlled  by  Assignable
                       Controller 2, the number switches  automatically  to
                       25.

    That means : in one part you only can choose one number for  Assignable
                 Controller 1 and only one number for Assignable Controller
                 2.

    It  is  possible  to  control  more  than  one  effect  by   the   same
    "Controller".  If  you  want, you can choose, that the Modulationswheel
    controls:

    Pitch, Filter  CutOff,
    Amplitude/Volume,
    LFO  Phase  Modulation,
    LFO  Frequency  Modulation,
    LFO  Amplitude  Modulation  and
    the Variationseffect.

@endnode

@node "XGCPVarfxValue" "Value of the choosen part"
@prev "XGCONTROLLERPANEL"

    @{b}@{u}Value of the choosen part@{uu}@{ub}

    Here you see the number of the part you connect the Variations-Effect
    to.
@endnode
@node XGVARFXPHASER "Phaser 1&2"

    @{b}@{u}Phaser 1 & 2@{uu}@{ub}

    The Phasereffect alters the phase of the signal cyclically and modulate
    the original with this signal.

    The Phaser1 has a mono input, Phaser2 a stereo one.

@endnode
@node VARFXDISTORTION "Distortion & Overdrive"

    @{b}@{u}Distortion & Overdrive@{uu}@{ub}

    This are the well known fuzzing sound for guitars, but also god to use,
    to create new sounds.

    That are most neccessary to create a Leadvoice for your  song.  Try  it
    ... its fantasic and has a big range of sound.

@endnode
@node VARFXAMP "Guitar-Amp Simulator"

    @{b}@{u}Guitar-Amp Simulator@{uu}@{ub}

    With this effect, you can simulate the sound of difference Guitar-Amps.

    There are three variations. So you can make, that, for example, a  bass
    guitar will sound like in the 60th.

@endnode
@node VARFXEQ "3(mono) & 2(stereo)-Band Equalizer"

    @{b}@{u}3(mono)- & 2(stereo)-Band Equalizer@{uu}@{ub}

    That are so called parametric  equalizers.  You  can  choose  with  the
    "...Freq"-slider the frequence you will influence.

    With the "...Gain"-slider you can alter the volume  of  this  frequence
    (and the range near by).

    To find the frequence, you will alter, bring the gain-slider to max and
    than move the "...Freq"-slider. (A sound must be heared.)

    After you had found the frequence, you can choose the gain you want ...

@endnode
@node VARFXAUTOWAH "Auto-Wah"

    @{b}@{u}Auto-Wah@{uu}@{ub}

    Normaly this guitar-effect will be controlled by a  foot-controller  at
    the stage.

    This effect will work here automaticly. You can influence it in  a  big
    range.

    Have fun ... :-))

@endnode
@node XGREVERBREAD "Read"

    @{b}@{u}Read@{uu}@{ub}

    By pressing this gadget the tool will try to  read  XGReverb-data  from
    Track into the tool.

    This data MUST NOT be writte before with my XGReverbEditor.  But  there
    must be at first a SysEx-entry with the Reverb-type.

    You will see, how usefull this function is ... :-))

@endnode
@node WHATISNEW "What is new ?"

    @{b}@{u}What is new ?@{uu}@{ub}

    The most important innovation is the:

    @{b}Read - function@{ub} in all tools.

    (not in the HEX-Transmitter, this is more an tool for experiments  with
    System Exclusive datas)

    Sometimes I had finished a song, I removed all tools and saved him. But
    later  I  found, that the sound shall be altered. In this case I had to
    open the SysEx-Editor (MagicWand in the Track-Editor click on  a  SysX)
    and alter the value by hand.

    Than close the Editor - start the sequencer to hear if it  is  right  -
    stop the sequencer - open the Editor - alter the value - and so on ...

    This is a hard work, if you have much SysEx-data in the track. So I get
    the idea to put a Read-function to all tools.

    During the work I realised, that is not so easy I've thought.  But  now
    I'm ready - all (I think) works fine.

    By this work I also removed so much bugs as possible and known by me.

    Some tools I have rewritten in big parts, to add the read-function.

    The XGMain-tool I've altered much more. Here I've inserted the knobs of
    the inovatools.library.

    With this new version all tools are downward compatible,  because  they
    are able to read all data from previous version.

    I hope you enjoy this version.

@endnode

